---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/site';

const steps = [
  {
    title: 'History and questions',
    body: 'The doctor asks about family eye history, your observations, and any concerns. Your gut feelings are data here; say them out loud.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Acuity check',
    body: 'Each eye reads a chart matched to the child\'s age: symbols or matching games for pre-readers, letters for older kids. This is the professionally run version of what home charts only approximate.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Alignment and movement',
    body: 'The doctor watches how the eyes point, track, and team up, often with a simple cover test: cover one eye, watch how the other responds. This is how strabismus is caught.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Refraction, usually with drops',
    body: 'Children\'s eyes focus so actively that an accurate prescription usually needs dilating drops (a cycloplegic refraction). The drops sting for a second and blur near vision for a few hours. This step is where hidden farsightedness and big left-right differences show up.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Eye health exam',
    body: 'A look at the structures of the eye, front and back, to rule out the rare but urgent stuff. Painless.',
  },
];

const bring = [
  'Any glasses the child already has',
  'A list of what you\'ve noticed, with rough dates',
  'Family eye history (amblyopia, strabismus, strong prescriptions in parents or siblings)',
  'Snacks and patience for the dilating-drop wait',
];
---

<Layout
  title="What an Eye Exam Looks Like"
  description="A plain-language guide to a child's comprehensive eye exam: who does it, what happens step by step, how the dilating drops feel, and what to bring. Nothing scary in it."
>
  <h1>What a comprehensive eye exam looks like.</h1>
  <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-lg text-ink/85">
    This whole site keeps pointing you to one place: a comprehensive eye exam by a
    professional. Fair enough, but what actually happens there? Here is the plain-language
    version, so the appointment feels routine instead of mysterious.
  </p>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <h2>Who does them.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Optometrists and ophthalmologists both perform comprehensive eye exams for children;
      some specialize in pediatrics. Your pediatrician can refer you, and no referral is
      required in most places. One important distinction: the quick vision check at school or
      at a well-child visit is a screening, not an exam. It is designed to flag kids who need
      the full workup, not to replace it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <h2>What happens, step by step.</h2>
    <ol class="mt-8 flex flex-col gap-8">
      {steps.map((s, i) => (
        <li class="flex gap-5">
          <div class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-teal font-display text-lg font-bold text-white">
            {i + 1}
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg">{s.title}</h3>
            <p class="mt-1 max-w-prose text-ink/85">{s.body}</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-8 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      The whole thing typically takes under an hour, most of it waiting for drops to work.
      Nothing hurts. Kids who were nervous going in usually leave holding a sticker.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <h2>What to bring.</h2>
    <ul class="mt-6 flex flex-col gap-3">
      {bring.map((b) => (
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="mt-1 h-2 w-2 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-sun" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span class="text-ink/85">{b}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <h2>Timing and cost.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends vision screening for all children at
      least once between ages 3 and 5, and professional groups support regular vision
      assessment through childhood. Many health plans cover pediatric eye exams as an
      essential benefit; ask your plan. For babies, InfantSEE, a public health program of the
      American Optometric Association, offers no-cost assessments between 6 and 12 months of
      age.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="mt-14">
    <Callout>
      <p><strong class="font-bold">If you remember one thing:</strong> parental instinct is a legitimate reason to book an exam. You do not need a failed screening, a referral, or an app's permission. If something feels off about how your child sees, make the appointment.</p>
    </Callout>
  </div>

  <section class="mt-14 border-t border-line pt-8">
    <h2 class="text-lg">Sources</h2>
    <ul class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-2 text-sm">
      <li><a href="https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/" rel="noopener" class="text-teal hover:text-teal-dark">U.S. Preventive Services Task Force</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.aao.org/" rel="noopener" class="text-teal hover:text-teal-dark">American Academy of Ophthalmology</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.aoa.org/" rel="noopener" class="text-teal hover:text-teal-dark">American Optometric Association</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.aapos.org/" rel="noopener" class="text-teal hover:text-teal-dark">AAPOS</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <div class="mt-16 flex flex-wrap gap-4">
    <a href={url('about-amblyopia/')} class="btn btn-primary">Understand amblyopia</a>
    <a href={url('glossary/')} class="btn btn-secondary">Glossary</a>
  </div>
</Layout>
